  + domain/failure-modes.md  (26 lines)

reasoning: The current worldview covers the basic domain model and lists open questions but stays safely within CRUD territory. I expanded outward in several directions: (1) Fairness as a first-class design concern, since the seed explicitly mentions it but the worldview only has FIFO implicitly. (2) The no-show problem, which is the #1 operational issue in real RSVP systems and isn't mentioned at all. (3) Group RSVPs, which break the 1-user-1-RSVP assumption and create complex capacity math. (4) Notification timing, because promotion from waitlist is meaningless if the user doesn't see it in time. (5) Recurring events, since most real events repeat and the isolated-event model is limiting. (6) Privacy, which the worldview completely ignores despite attendee lists being sensitive personal data. (7) Game theory, challenging the assumption that users behave honestly. (8) Concrete failure modes, turning the abstract open questions into specific scenarios that demand specific answers.

8 operation(s) (8 new)
applied 8 operation(s)
regenerating index...

[suggestions]
  LENS     adversarial-user
           The worldview assumes cooperative users. An adversarial lens would surface abuse patterns: scalping spots, griefing organizers with mass RSVPs, social engineering via attendee lists.
  LENS     scale-stress
           Everything changes at 10,000 concurrent RSVPs. Database locking strategies, notification throughput, and fairness algorithms all have different tradeoffs at scale.
  LENS     accessibility
           Physical accessibility requirements (wheelchair spots, sign language interpreters) create capacity sub-categories that the current flat model can't represent.
  QUESTION What happens when the organizer is also an attendee?
           Role overlap creates permission edge cases — can an organizer waitlist themselves? Skip the queue?
  QUESTION Should declined RSVPs be deletable or permanent records?
           This determines whether RSVP history is an audit log (append-only) or a mutable user preference, with cascading effects on analytics and privacy.
  QUESTION How should the system handle events that change capacity after RSVPs exist?
           Capacity reduction with existing acceptances is an unaddressed conflict between organizer control and attendee expectations.
  SOURCE   Roth, A.E. 'Who Gets What and Why' (2015)
           Nobel laureate's accessible treatment of matching markets and mechanism design — directly applicable to waitlist promotion and fairness models.
  SOURCE   Eventbrite's engineering blog on capacity management
           Real-world war stories from a platform handling millions of RSVPs, including their approach to race conditions and overbooking.
  QUESTION Is 'maybe' a real status or just polite noise?
           The 'maybe' RSVP status consumes no capacity but provides no commitment. It may add complexity without value — many systems (e.g., Eventbrite) don't offer it.

