=== STEP: storm-api ===
--- cmd: bny brane storm --yes RSVP UX patterns — what makes a great event platform API? ---
storming: inline...

[intake]
  + domain/api-design-patterns.md  (73 lines)
  + domain/rsvp-state-machine.md  (62 lines)
  + domain/undo-and-forgiveness.md  (42 lines)
  + domain/real-time-and-live-updates.md  (45 lines)
  + domain/progressive-disclosure-api.md  (69 lines)
  + domain/event-discovery-social-graph.md  (49 lines)
  + domain/organizer-experience-api.md  (50 lines)
  + domain/time-as-design-material.md  (65 lines)
  + domain/error-recovery-ux.md  (86 lines)

reasoning: The current worldview is deep on backend concerns (concurrency, isolation levels, distributed systems) and behavioral/economic dynamics (game theory, no-shows, fairness). What's almost entirely missing is the UX and API design layer — which is exactly what the seed asks about. I explored: (1) API design patterns — how REST conventions map to RSVP semantics, error design as UX, the waitlist-is-it-an-error question; (2) State machine formalization — making implicit states explicit, the re-RSVP problem; (3) Undo and forgiveness — grace periods, soft deletes, organizer mistake recovery; (4) Real-time updates — WebSockets vs polling, the false-hope problem of showing exact counts; (5) Progressive disclosure — serving both simple integrators and platform builders; (6) Social graph and discovery — the hidden graph in RSVP data; (7) Organizer experience — the underserved supply side of the platform; (8) Time as design material — registration windows, phases, timezone display; (9) Error recovery — actionable errors, degraded operation, partial success.

9 operation(s) (9 new)
applied 9 operation(s)
regenerating index...

[suggestions]
  LENS     mobile-first
           The worldview assumes desktop API consumers. Mobile clients face unique constraints: unreliable networks, battery-conscious polling, offline-first patterns, push notification limitations. A mobile-first lens would reshape API design around latency tolerance, payload size, and intermittent connectivity.
  LENS     skeptic
           The worldview assumes RSVP systems need all this complexity. A skeptic would ask: do most events actually hit capacity? Is the waitlist used? Are race conditions a real problem at typical scale? Premature engineering for edge cases may be the bigger risk than the edge cases themselves.
  QUESTION What does the check-in experience look like and how does it feed back into the RSVP data model?
           The worldview ends at the event door. Check-in is where RSVP promises meet reality — no-show marking, walk-ins, actual vs expected attendance. This data closes the loop for reputation systems and demand forecasting.
  QUESTION How should the API handle event modifications after RSVPs exist?
           Changing a venue, time, or date after 50 people RSVPed is common but unexplored. Does a time change require re-confirmation? Should users be auto-declined if they indicated time-based availability? This is a rich edge case area.
  QUESTION What does the onboarding flow look like for a zero-config RSVP?
           The simplest possible RSVP is an unauthenticated form with just a name and email — no account required. How does this interact with the user model, duplicate detection, and later account creation? Many successful event platforms (Lu.ma, Partiful) optimize for frictionless first RSVP.
  SOURCE   Designing Web APIs by Brenda Jin, Saurabh Sahni, Amir Shevat (O'Reilly)
           Covers progressive disclosure, error design, pagination, and versioning patterns specifically for API design — directly relevant to making the RSVP API developer-friendly.
  SOURCE   Partiful and Lu.ma as case studies
           Both are modern RSVP platforms that prioritize UX over technical completeness. Studying their flows would ground the theoretical worldview in real product decisions — especially around frictionless RSVP, social features, and mobile-first design.

