🐰 brane  25 files, 1 dirs

domain/
  failure-modes.md                      A catalog of concrete failure scenarios with cross-references to the architectural patterns that address each one.
  no-show-problem.md                    Free events see 30-50% no-show rates — the biggest operational failure in RSVP systems is not technical but behavioral.
  event-rsvp-core.md                    A Rails API for managing events with RSVP tracking, capacity limits, and automatic waitlist promotion — the foundational entities and behaviors that every other file in this knowledge base builds on.
  weighted-lottery-allocation.md        A weighted lottery gives every eligible person a chance proportional to how many fairness criteria they satisfy — more nuanced than strict priority or pure randomness.
  error-recovery-ux.md                  The best APIs tell you exactly what went wrong and what to do next — every error response should answer: what happened, why, and what can the user do.
  fairness-models.md                    No allocation system is universally fair — the choice of fairness model is a values statement about the community, not a technical decision.
  capacity-as-inventory.md              Event capacity is perishable inventory — an empty seat at a past event has zero value, justifying more aggressive management than durable goods.
  api-design-patterns.md                A great event API is one developers can guess correctly before reading the docs.
  notification-timing.md                When and how users are notified shapes their experience more than the underlying data model — a silent promotion is a wasted promotion.
  rsvp-state-machine.md                 Every RSVP bug is a state transition that shouldn't have been allowed.
  time-as-design-material.md            Every feature in an RSVP system interacts with time in non-obvious ways — time zones, lifecycle phases, and registration windows are architectural concerns, not display concerns.
  undo-and-forgiveness.md               The best UX assumes users will make mistakes — a 5-minute undo window for cancellations dramatically reduces regret-driven support tickets without compromising fairness.
  idempotency-and-retry-safety.md       Every mutation in a distributed RSVP system must be safe to retry, because "did my request succeed?" is sometimes unanswerable.
  event-discovery-social-graph.md       RSVP data is a social graph in disguise — co-attendance patterns reveal interests and relationships, but analyzing them conflicts with privacy-by-default.
  event-series-recurring.md             The simplest RSVP model treats events as isolated instances, but recurring events (weekly meetups, annual conferences, multi-session workshops) require either a first-class series entity or carefully managed individual events.
  game-theory-rsvps.md                  RSVP systems create strategic incentives that rational users will exploit — the rules you choose determine the equilibrium behavior of your users.
  progressive-disclosure-api.md         A great API serves both the 5-minute integration and the 5-month deep build — by making simple things simple and complex things possible.
  privacy-and-visibility.md             Attendee list visibility is a safety issue, not just a preference — visible lists reveal planned location and time, creating stalking risk.
  concurrency-patterns-reservations.md  Multiple actors competing for finite capacity requires explicit concurrency control — the default (READ COMMITTED without locking) silently allows overbooking.
  group-rsvps-and-plus-ones.md          A group RSVP for N people consumes N capacity slots, creating partial-fit problems that don't exist in the one-person-one-RSVP model.
  real-time-and-live-updates.md         Users staring at a full event page want to know the instant a spot opens — but real-time capacity displays can cause more problems than they solve.
  organizer-experience-api.md           Organizers create the supply — their needs are batch-oriented, analytics-heavy, and dashboard-shaped, fundamentally different from the single-event attendee experience.
  open-questions.md                     Remaining unresolved decisions not yet addressed by other files in this knowledge base.
  distributed-failure-modes.md          The RSVP system becomes a distributed system the moment you add background jobs, email services, or multiple app servers — and distributed systems fail in ways that single-process systems cannot.
  isolation-levels-and-anomalies.md     The isolation level determines which concurrency bugs are possible — READ COMMITTED (Rails/PostgreSQL default) allows the most common reservation overbooking bug.

